The paper introduces a new security game model that uses computational game models to address resource allocation challenges in the security domain. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a new algorithm to determine the equilibrium strategy, which involves matrix decomposition and random low-dimensional embedding, indicating that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the impact of the proposed model on fields such as military attack and defense, financial system security, political campaign, and civil safeguarding, suggesting that it may belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper presents a series of constructions to show that the proposed method achieves asymptotic zero error, indicating that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
